1
00:00:09,384 --> 00:00:11,797
[woman screaming]

2
00:00:20,187 --> 00:00:22,179
[screaming continues]

3
00:00:31,490 --> 00:00:33,823
[screaming continues]

4
00:00:49,341 --> 00:00:52,175
[screaming continues]

5
00:01:03,814 --> 00:01:05,646
[man narrating]
<i>To EdgarAllan Poe,</i>

6
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:08,816
<i>whose stories have inspired
this motion picture.</i>

7
00:01:19,371 --> 00:01:21,784
[chorus singing in Latin]

8
00:01:39,391 --> 00:01:42,008
[singing continues]

9
00:01:52,863 --> 00:01:55,196
[woman] Is that an accusation,
Mr. Pike?

10
00:01:56,491 --> 00:01:58,483
Is that some sort of
an accusation?

11
00:02:01,538 --> 00:02:03,825
Is that some sort of
an accusation, Mr. Pike?

12
00:02:03,915 --> 00:02:07,408
- [man] What'd you say?
- Nothing. Nothing.

13
00:02:07,502 --> 00:02:10,495
- I thought you said something.
- No.

14
00:02:12,341 --> 00:02:14,298
I was just talking to myself.
It's nothing.

15
00:02:40,285 --> 00:02:42,277
[clock ticking]

16
00:02:46,958 --> 00:02:50,668
He's liquidating a substantial
number of his assets here.

17
00:02:52,047 --> 00:02:56,883
This represents 15,
possibly 20 percent of his holdings.

18
00:02:56,968 --> 00:03:01,178
I wouldn't know. Ernie has never talked
to me much about business.

19
00:03:01,264 --> 00:03:03,256
Perhaps if he'd be willing
to wait until...

20
00:03:03,350 --> 00:03:05,012
He can't wait, Mr. Pike.

21
00:03:05,102 --> 00:03:08,891
The doctors give him three weeks.
Six at the most.

22
00:03:09,398 --> 00:03:11,731
Ernie wants this done now.

23
00:03:11,817 --> 00:03:14,275
With all the proceeds going to you.

24
00:03:14,361 --> 00:03:17,069
- That's right.
- Bad timing.

25
00:03:17,155 --> 00:03:21,149
The market price on some of these stocks
is lower than it's been in years.

26
00:03:22,035 --> 00:03:25,028
Why doesn't he simply put
these assets in your name?

27
00:03:25,122 --> 00:03:29,162
I don't need assets, Mr. Pike.
I need dollars to live on.

28
00:03:29,251 --> 00:03:32,915
You've been remembered,
quite generously, in the will.

29
00:03:33,004 --> 00:03:36,168
And how long will it take
to settle the estate, Mr. Pike?

30
00:03:36,675 --> 00:03:39,383
Eighteen months. Two years.

31
00:03:39,469 --> 00:03:41,631
- Depending on...
- What do I do while I'm waiting?

32
00:03:41,722 --> 00:03:43,384
Take a job as a waitress?

33
00:03:43,890 --> 00:03:45,927
I'm not society, Mr. Pike.

34
00:03:46,017 --> 00:03:47,679
I have nothing of my own.

35
00:03:48,979 --> 00:03:52,518
I was a flight attendant
that Ernie brought home off the red-eye...

36
00:03:52,607 --> 00:03:56,692
to the shock and dismay of you
and everyone else in this town.

37
00:03:56,778 --> 00:03:59,816
I married a rich, old man.

38
00:03:59,906 --> 00:04:03,866
I let him use me...
for pleasure and for show.

39
00:04:05,871 --> 00:04:08,454
Now I'm going to let him
pay me for my services.

40
00:04:08,540 --> 00:04:11,499
[clock chiming]

41
00:04:26,099 --> 00:04:28,341
This is Ernest's signature?

42
00:04:28,435 --> 00:04:30,597
Is that some sort of
an accusation, Mr. Pike?

43
00:04:42,866 --> 00:04:45,279
Hello, Ernie. Yes.

44
00:04:46,912 --> 00:04:49,154
Yes. I'm here with Steven Pike.

45
00:04:49,247 --> 00:04:53,082
I gave him the papers.
I don't think he likes it very much.

46
00:04:54,336 --> 00:04:56,293
- [clock ticking]
- Well...

47
00:04:57,005 --> 00:04:58,462
are you sure you're up to it?

48
00:05:00,425 --> 00:05:02,132
All right. I'll put him on.

49
00:05:08,099 --> 00:05:10,762
[ticking continues]

50
00:05:10,852 --> 00:05:14,641
- Hello, Ernest.
- [Ernest] <i>Hello, Steven.</i>

51
00:05:15,190 --> 00:05:18,058
How are you feeling?
How's the pain?

52
00:05:18,151 --> 00:05:20,017
Are you feeling much pain?

53
00:05:20,111 --> 00:05:23,024
[Ernest] <i>No. No pain.</i>

54
00:05:23,448 --> 00:05:24,448
[Pike] Listen, Ernest.

55
00:05:25,408 --> 00:05:28,992
I have these papers here,
the ones you sent.

56
00:05:29,371 --> 00:05:30,532
<i>Yes?</i>

57
00:05:31,540 --> 00:05:34,032
Are you sure
you want to do this?

58
00:05:34,125 --> 00:05:36,082
Have you thought this through?

59
00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:39,833
<i>Yes. I want to do it,
Steven.</i>

60
00:05:39,923 --> 00:05:42,165
<i>I owe it to Jessica.</i>

61
00:05:42,884 --> 00:05:44,420
- [man] <i>Hello?</i>
- Yes?

62
00:05:44,511 --> 00:05:47,754
<i>- Who is this?</i>
- I'm Steven Pike, Mr. Valdemar's attorney.

63
00:05:47,848 --> 00:05:50,340
<i>Bob Hoffman, Mr. Pike.
I'm Ernie's doctor.</i>

64
00:05:50,433 --> 00:05:54,017
<i>Look. Is all this really necessary?
Uh, Ernie's...</i>

65
00:05:54,104 --> 00:05:55,845
<i>Well, he needs as much rest
as he can get.</i>

66
00:05:55,939 --> 00:05:57,771
<i>So, unless this is
something really urgent...</i>

67
00:05:57,858 --> 00:06:03,570
Well, Ernest is asking me
to do something a bit, uh, unorthodox.

68
00:06:03,655 --> 00:06:07,239
Something that's, uh,
very unlike him to do.

69
00:06:07,325 --> 00:06:11,945
<i>People with Ernest's prognosis will often
do surprising things, Mr. Pike.</i>

70
00:06:12,038 --> 00:06:14,405
<i>I can assure you his mind
is as sharp as ever.</i>

71
00:06:14,499 --> 00:06:17,037
I see. I see.
Thank you, Doctor. I...

72
00:06:17,127 --> 00:06:19,585
I hope I haven't disturbed him
too much.

73
00:06:19,671 --> 00:06:21,412
<i>I just don't want him agitated.
That's all.</i>

74
00:06:21,506 --> 00:06:24,670
<i>- I'm sure you understand.</i>
- [Pike] Yes. Yes, of course. Yes, uh...

75
00:06:24,759 --> 00:06:27,001
- Good-bye, Doctor.
<i>- Good-bye.</i>

76
00:06:34,185 --> 00:06:35,847
I'll prepare the necessary forms

77
00:06:35,937 --> 00:06:37,929
and mail them to you
for Ernest's signature.

78
00:06:38,023 --> 00:06:40,982
Well, I wouldn't want any delays.
I'll stop by and pick them up.

79
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:44,023
Tomorrow morning.
They'll be ready, I hope?

80
00:06:45,488 --> 00:06:47,605
- They'll be ready.
- Thank you.

81
00:06:48,533 --> 00:06:50,115
Have a nice day, Mr. Pike.

82
00:07:28,490 --> 00:07:30,482
[ice cubes rattling]

83
00:08:02,190 --> 00:08:04,182
- [ticking]
- [machine beeping]

84
00:08:10,824 --> 00:08:13,066
- God, he's still...
- Still under.

85
00:08:14,077 --> 00:08:16,740
Still completely at my command.

86
00:08:16,830 --> 00:08:18,822
- [ticking continues]
- [beeping continues]

87
00:08:19,666 --> 00:08:21,532
- Valdemar.
- [dial tone]

88
00:08:21,626 --> 00:08:23,117
Repeat these words.

89
00:08:24,671 --> 00:08:25,912
I want to do it.

90
00:08:26,756 --> 00:08:28,418
I owe it to JJessica.

91
00:08:28,967 --> 00:08:32,927
I want to do it.
I owe it to Jessica.

92
00:08:33,888 --> 00:08:35,754
- Wake him up.
- [handset settles in cradle]

93
00:08:35,849 --> 00:08:39,513
To the pain?
To the realization that he's dying?

94
00:08:40,937 --> 00:08:42,678
He's better off where he is.

95
00:08:45,483 --> 00:08:46,564
Besides,

96
00:08:47,610 --> 00:08:49,351
I thought if we let him sleep,

97
00:08:50,280 --> 00:08:53,773
we might be able to have some time,
liquidate a few assets of our own.

98
00:08:53,867 --> 00:08:56,655
- Robert! What if he...
- What? What if he hears me?

99
00:08:56,745 --> 00:08:58,407
Well, I'm sure he can. Valdemar.

100
00:08:58,955 --> 00:09:00,947
- Do you hear me?
- Yes.

101
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:04,663
- I hear you.
- Fascinating.

102
00:09:04,753 --> 00:09:08,372
Somewhere deep in his consciousness
he knows exactly what we're doing to him.

103
00:09:09,049 --> 00:09:11,507
But when I wake him,
it'll all disappear.

104
00:09:13,136 --> 00:09:15,002
Like the fragments of a dream.

105
00:09:15,096 --> 00:09:16,507
I don't find it fascinating.

106
00:09:18,266 --> 00:09:19,347
It's morbid.

107
00:09:21,061 --> 00:09:22,097
Frightening.

108
00:09:22,187 --> 00:09:24,725
- [beeping continues]
- [ticking continues]

109
00:09:25,982 --> 00:09:28,895
I'm not as...
vindictive as you are.

110
00:09:28,985 --> 00:09:30,692
I don't take
any pleasure out of this.

111
00:09:31,696 --> 00:09:36,066
He's a ruthless old man who treats people
as if they were possessions.

112
00:09:36,159 --> 00:09:39,277
He spent his life taking whatever
he wanted without a care for anyone else.

113
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:43,785
He took you away from me.
Vindictive? Yes. Yes, I am vindictive.

114
00:09:43,875 --> 00:09:45,787
He didn't take me.
I went.

115
00:09:45,877 --> 00:09:47,117
He didn't know
I was seeing you.

116
00:09:47,170 --> 00:09:49,065
He doesn't even realize
we knew each other bef...

117
00:09:49,089 --> 00:09:53,049
- I want you back, Jess.
- Robert. Please. I can't.

118
00:09:53,134 --> 00:09:54,841
Not now. I couldn't.

119
00:09:56,304 --> 00:09:58,717
I-I'm having a very
difficult time with this. I...

120
00:09:59,682 --> 00:10:04,677
I need you to try to be sensitive to that,
try to understand how hard this is for me.

121
00:10:05,688 --> 00:10:08,709
- If you want me to go through with it...
- You already have gone through with this.

122
00:10:08,733 --> 00:10:10,349
There's no turning back anymore.

123
00:10:10,443 --> 00:10:13,443
What are you gonna tell Mr. Pike?
"Oh, this has all been a misunderstanding.

124
00:10:13,863 --> 00:10:15,820
I didn't realize my husband
was under hypnosis

125
00:10:15,907 --> 00:10:17,648
when I asked him to sign
the papers."

126
00:10:17,742 --> 00:10:20,109
You won't like it in prison, Jessica.
The food's awful.

127
00:10:22,330 --> 00:10:24,242
And let's call a spade a spade, all right?

128
00:10:24,332 --> 00:10:27,496
This was your idea, not mine.
I was willing to wait.

129
00:10:27,585 --> 00:10:30,874
I just wanted us to be together again,
but that wasn't good enough, was it?

130
00:10:30,964 --> 00:10:33,081
Not after you got a taste
of what it was to be rich.

131
00:10:33,174 --> 00:10:35,111
You're going to pretend
you don't care about the money?

132
00:10:35,135 --> 00:10:36,501
No. Of course I want the money,

133
00:10:36,594 --> 00:10:39,007
but I want you too,
and I thought you wanted me.

134
00:10:39,097 --> 00:10:40,213
I do.

135
00:10:42,767 --> 00:10:44,349
Robert, I do. Uh...

136
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:46,518
It's just difficult...

137
00:10:47,063 --> 00:10:49,771
Difficult to care about someone
you know is a thief?

138
00:10:51,985 --> 00:10:52,985
I know.

139
00:10:54,195 --> 00:10:55,652
I have the same problem.

140
00:11:04,205 --> 00:11:05,616
- [beeping]
- [ticking stops]

141
00:11:05,707 --> 00:11:09,075
Valdemar.
I'm going to wake you now.

142
00:11:10,336 --> 00:11:11,793
When I count to five,

143
00:11:12,297 --> 00:11:15,461
you will be completely awake
and alert.

144
00:11:16,759 --> 00:11:17,759
One.

145
00:11:18,678 --> 00:11:20,510
You will not remember anything.

146
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:25,345
Two. You're starting
to regain your senses.

147
00:11:26,477 --> 00:11:29,811
Three. Starting to see the room.

148
00:11:29,898 --> 00:11:31,514
Starting to see me.

149
00:11:33,026 --> 00:11:34,107
Four.

150
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:38,647
[Ernest] Oh, God! The pain!

151
00:11:38,740 --> 00:11:40,322
[screaming]

152
00:11:40,408 --> 00:11:42,115
God. Can't you help him?

153
00:11:42,911 --> 00:11:45,244
He'll be asleep soon.
He's had his injection.

154
00:11:45,330 --> 00:11:46,616
There's not much else I can do.

155
00:11:46,706 --> 00:11:49,949
[sighs] You could stay with him.
That's what you're being paid for.

156
00:11:50,043 --> 00:11:51,909
You should have him in a hospital.

157
00:11:52,587 --> 00:11:54,499
A man in his advanced state.

158
00:11:54,964 --> 00:11:58,128
Keeping him at home.
I have never seen anything like it.

159
00:11:58,218 --> 00:12:00,881
In all my years of nursing,
I've never seen anything like it.

160
00:12:01,262 --> 00:12:04,255
[Ernest moaning]

161
00:12:11,064 --> 00:12:14,648
[Ernest] Where is
that bitch of a wife of mine?

162
00:12:16,486 --> 00:12:17,897
Where is she?

163
00:12:18,446 --> 00:12:21,029
Out spending my money.

164
00:12:22,283 --> 00:12:24,866
Where is she? Where...

165
00:12:26,663 --> 00:12:28,029
Jessica!

166
00:12:29,040 --> 00:12:30,326
Jessica!

167
00:12:34,629 --> 00:12:36,165
Jessica!

168
00:12:43,638 --> 00:12:45,095
Jessica!

169
00:12:45,181 --> 00:12:49,016
[TV: loud noises]

170
00:12:53,314 --> 00:12:56,022
Two of the money market accounts
are with the local bank.

171
00:12:56,109 --> 00:13:00,194
Those funds are available to you now.
See Mr. Pratt.

172
00:13:00,655 --> 00:13:02,897
The rest is going to take some time.

173
00:13:03,783 --> 00:13:06,150
- How much time?
- Paperwork, mails,

174
00:13:06,244 --> 00:13:08,361
out-of-town checks
will have to clear.

175
00:13:08,955 --> 00:13:10,446
Two to three weeks.

176
00:13:15,211 --> 00:13:17,294
If anything should happen to Ernest,

177
00:13:17,380 --> 00:13:19,747
you'll have a hard time collecting,
I'm afraid.

178
00:13:20,383 --> 00:13:22,545
So do your best to keep him alive,
won't you?

179
00:13:22,635 --> 00:13:25,969
- I'll do my best.
- I'm sure you will.

180
00:13:35,023 --> 00:13:38,983
This is quite a lot to be walking
around with in cash, Mrs. Valdemar.

181
00:13:39,068 --> 00:13:41,310
Now, we do offer
a liquid asset account

182
00:13:41,404 --> 00:13:43,270
that would allow you
to withdraw any amount...

183
00:13:43,364 --> 00:13:45,026
I'll be wanting to talk
to you about that.

184
00:13:45,116 --> 00:13:48,609
I'll be coming into quite a large sum
in the next few weeks.

185
00:13:48,703 --> 00:13:50,660
Something over three million,
I'm told.

186
00:13:51,706 --> 00:13:55,541
And, of course, I'll be wanting to put it
someplace where it will be safe.

187
00:13:56,002 --> 00:13:59,712
But this... I have a need
for this in cash.

188
00:13:59,797 --> 00:14:01,754
Whatever you say,
Mrs. Valdemar.

189
00:14:01,841 --> 00:14:04,128
Whenever you're ready,
just give me a call.

190
00:14:04,218 --> 00:14:07,006
We're, uh...
We're here to please.

191
00:14:21,944 --> 00:14:23,936
[whirring]

192
00:14:28,993 --> 00:14:30,700
That's good enough, Martha. You can go.

193
00:14:30,787 --> 00:14:33,780
- We've not done the upstairs yet, Mrs. V.
- It doesn't need to be done.

194
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:36,536
It's fine. Really.
You can get it next time.

195
00:14:36,626 --> 00:14:38,162
If you say so, mum.

196
00:14:38,252 --> 00:14:41,916
All right, people.
Let's pack it up. We're leaving.

197
00:14:42,006 --> 00:14:45,124
Mr. V seems in
a bad way today, mum.

198
00:14:45,843 --> 00:14:48,551
Yes. He's, uh, been bad
for some time now.

199
00:14:48,638 --> 00:14:52,473
Poor old soul. Night nurse left,
and I didn't know what to do.

200
00:14:52,558 --> 00:14:54,675
I'm sorry. I didn't expect
to be gone so long.

201
00:14:54,769 --> 00:14:57,182
That's all right.
Doctor's with him now.

202
00:14:57,271 --> 00:14:59,012
Oh, he's here? Good.

203
00:15:07,365 --> 00:15:09,357
[door closes]

204
00:15:43,067 --> 00:15:45,480
- [machine beeping]
- [ticking]

205
00:15:45,570 --> 00:15:49,655
[Robert] Sign your name, Valdemar.
Sign your name on the line.

206
00:16:01,252 --> 00:16:02,834
Again, Valdemar.

207
00:16:05,965 --> 00:16:07,797
Here. On the line.

208
00:16:08,342 --> 00:16:09,753
Sign your name again.

209
00:16:09,844 --> 00:16:12,461
[beeping continues]

210
00:16:28,362 --> 00:16:29,773
Done.

211
00:16:29,864 --> 00:16:31,901
- Is he...
- Still under.

212
00:16:34,285 --> 00:16:35,366
Come here.

213
00:16:37,538 --> 00:16:39,245
Are you sure you want to?

214
00:16:42,001 --> 00:16:43,333
Yes.

215
00:16:49,133 --> 00:16:50,669
What did you put
in the safe, Jesse?

216
00:16:50,760 --> 00:16:52,797
[chuckles]
The safe?

217
00:16:54,055 --> 00:16:55,421
When you came in.

218
00:16:56,098 --> 00:16:58,841
I saw you put something
in the safe. What was it?

219
00:16:58,935 --> 00:17:00,176
[Jessica] Money.

220
00:17:01,729 --> 00:17:04,437
- You got the money.
- Some.

221
00:17:06,150 --> 00:17:08,984
- Just a little.
- How much is a little?

222
00:17:10,029 --> 00:17:13,147
[Jessica] I don't know.
A few thousand.

223
00:17:15,618 --> 00:17:17,575
None of it mine, I suppose.

224
00:17:18,246 --> 00:17:20,158
I'll have the rest in
a few weeks.

225
00:17:20,248 --> 00:17:22,831
Oh. Nothing for me
until the job is finished.

226
00:17:22,917 --> 00:17:24,954
- Is that it?
- [chuckles]

227
00:17:25,503 --> 00:17:26,994
That's not fair.

228
00:17:28,297 --> 00:17:30,880
I haven't gotten anything
out of this, Jess.

229
00:17:30,967 --> 00:17:32,253
Soon.

230
00:17:33,261 --> 00:17:34,797
In a few weeks.

231
00:17:36,097 --> 00:17:37,963
In a few weeks we'll have it all.

232
00:17:39,141 --> 00:17:41,633
Just think of it.
A million dollars.

233
00:17:43,104 --> 00:17:45,642
A million dollars
for us to share.

234
00:17:51,153 --> 00:17:52,985
Mine in cash.
Remember?

235
00:17:54,949 --> 00:17:56,360
No checks.

236
00:17:57,577 --> 00:18:00,866
- Nothing with my name on it.
- Ah, don't worry.

237
00:18:01,622 --> 00:18:05,081
- Nothing to connect us.
- There's nothing to connect us.

238
00:18:06,669 --> 00:18:08,877
Nothing at all to connect us.

239
00:18:11,215 --> 00:18:13,207
[machine beeping]

240
00:18:17,054 --> 00:18:18,261
It's Ernest.

241
00:18:28,232 --> 00:18:31,020
[steady beep]

242
00:18:46,584 --> 00:18:47,950
Oh, my God.

243
